@node General "mFinger ÀáUsage - General"
@{u}Usage - General@{uu}
mFinger should be very easy to use, at least that is the intention.  To
finger an address simply start the program and type in an address in the
string gadget.  Press enter on your keyboard or the finger button in the GUI.
Could it be easier?  Addresses you haven't fingered before will be added to
the addresslist.  To see the addresslist, press the popup gadget next to the
string gadget.  The window that opens has two a listview with two columns and
some buttons.  You can sort the addresses by dragging them them around in the
listview, or do it alphabetically by pressing the Sort button.  Clicking an
address makes it the current address for editing, press the Edit button to
open the edit window.  Any changes you do in the string gadgets in the edit
window are immediatedly reflected in the listview.  Doubleclicking an address
fingers it.

You can copy text to the clipboard by marking it with the mouse in the main
window listview and selecting the Edit/Copy menuitem (or pressing R-Amiga-C).
Selecting Edit/Clear in the menu clears the main window listview of any text.
A separatorbar will be inserted between the finger output from two different
addresses.

Note that when fingering you usually just type in the email address (in the
form user@host) of the person you're interested in.  You can also leave out
the user part of the address and just enter a host, some sites allow this and
will tell you which users are currently logged on.

Enjoy.
@endnode

@node ARexx "mFinger ÀáARexx interface"
@{u}ARexx interface@{uu}
mFinger can be controlled through its arexx port.  For information about how
to create ARexx scripts, you should refer to the manuals that came with your
computer.

In order for ARexx to work SYS:System/RexxMaster needs to be running and
ARexx needs to be turned on in the MUI configuration.

The arguments for the commands works exactly like ordinary AmigaDOS command
arguments with respect to the flags /A, /S, etc.

The following commands are available.

@{b}QUIT FORCE/S@{ub}
Ends mFinger.

@{b}HIDE@{ub}
Hides (iconifies) mFinger.

@{b}SHOW@{ub}
Shows (pops up) an iconified mFinger.

@{b}INFO ITEM/A@{ub}
According to the given parameter the result string is filled with
the following contents:

   - "title"       Title of the mFinger

   - "author"      Author of the mFinger

   - "copyright"   Copyright message

   - "description" Short description

   - "version"     Version string

   - "base"        Name of the ARexx port

   - "screen"      Name of the public screen

@{b}HELP FILE/A@{ub}
A list of all ARexx commands available in mFinger is written into the given
file.

@{b}FINGER ADDRESS/A@{ub}
Fingers the supplied address.  Starting a new finger will abort one that is
already in progress.  Note that this command is asynchronous.  This means
that the command will return before the finger has been performed.  Thus it
will always appear to be successful (the returncode is always RC_OK) and you
have no way of knowing when mFinger is done fingering.

@{b}ABORT@{ub}
Abort a finger in progress, does nothing if no finger is going on.

@{b}CLEAR@{ub}
Clears the main window listview.

@{u}Example ARexx script@{uu}
Included in this archive is an example script for use with AmIRC.  Load the
script into an editor and modify the line that starts with "mFingerCmd = " to
suit your setup.  Then install the script in your AmIRC/Rexx directory and
make an alias like this:
  FINGER = /RX MFINGER %p

Now you'll be able to type "/finger nickname" in AmIRC to finger the person
with the supplied nickname.  If mFinger isn't running, it will be launched,
and if it is running it will be told to do the fingering thorugh arexx.

The wonders of modern technology, eh?
@endnode

